AI referral traffic grew **778%** year-over-year in 2025 (Similarweb). That is the single most-cited statistic in every AI search discussion — and it deserves context. AI search is the biggest shift in how people find information since mobile overtook desktop. ChatGPT now processes **2 billion queries daily**. Google AI Overviews appear on millions of search results. Perplexity handles **780 million monthly queries**. But the data tells a nuanced story. That **778%** growth started from a tiny base. AI platforms drove **2 billion total visits** in 2025 — significant, but a fraction of Google's **191 billion referrals** in the same period. Organic search still dominates. The transformation is real, but it is early. This page collects every meaningful AI search statistic available, sourced and cited, so you can make decisions based on data rather than hype.

## AI Search Market Overview

The AI search landscape in 2026 is dominated by three platforms: ChatGPT, Google AI Overviews, and Perplexity. Each operates differently, but together they represent a fundamental shift in how users interact with search.

### ChatGPT Usage Statistics

- **800 million** weekly active users as of early 2026 (DemandSage)
- **2 billion** daily queries processed (DemandSage)
- **77.97%** of all AI-driven visit share — nearly 4 out of 5 AI referral visits come from ChatGPT (SE Ranking)
- **400 million** weekly active users were reported in February 2025, meaning ChatGPT doubled its user base in under 12 months (OpenAI)
- **200 million** monthly active users had been the benchmark in August 2024 (OpenAI)
- ChatGPT became the fastest product to reach **300 million** weekly users in December 2024 (OpenAI)

### Perplexity Usage Statistics

- **780 million** monthly queries as of late 2025 (DemandSage)
- **15.1%** of global AI-driven traffic share (SE Ranking)
- **19.7%** AI traffic share in the United States specifically — higher than its global average (SE Ranking)
- **4.1%** AI traffic share in the United Kingdom (SE Ranking)
- Perplexity's referral traffic grew faster than any other AI platform in percentage terms during 2025 (Similarweb)

### Total AI Search Traffic

- **2 billion** total visits referred by AI platforms in 2025 (Similarweb)
- **778%** year-over-year growth in AI referral traffic (Similarweb)
- AI search still accounts for approximately **1%** of total web traffic globally (BrightEdge)
- Google referred **191 billion** visits in the same period — roughly **96x** the volume of all AI platforms combined (Similarweb)
- AI referral traffic share grew from **0.1%** to approximately **1%** during 2025 (Conductor)

The trajectory matters more than the current share. At **778%** annual growth, AI referral traffic doubles roughly every 2–3 months. If that rate sustains — even at a decelerated pace — AI platforms will represent a meaningful share of total web traffic within 18–24 months.

## Google AI Overviews Statistics

Google AI Overviews (formerly Search Generative Experience) are the most consequential development for SEO since featured snippets. They appear directly in Google search results, answering queries before users reach organic listings.

### Appearance Rates

- AI Overviews appear in approximately **13%** of US desktop queries as of early 2026 (Search Engine Land)
- AI Overviews peaked at appearing in **60%** of tracked queries in November 2025 before Google pulled back significantly (Xponent21)
- The pullback from **60%** to **13%** suggests Google is cautiously managing quality and user satisfaction
- AI Overviews are more common for informational queries (**25–30%** appearance rate) than transactional queries (**5–8%**) (Search Engine Land)
- YMYL (Your Money or Your Life) topics see lower AI Overview rates — health and finance queries trigger them less frequently

### Click-Through Rate Impact

The impact on organic click-through rates is substantial and well-documented:

- Organic CTR dropped **61%** when AI Overviews appear — from **1.76%** to **0.61%** (Seer Interactive)
- Paid ad CTR dropped **68%** when AI Overviews are present (Seer Interactive)
- However, brands cited within AI Overviews earn **35%** more organic clicks than they would without the AI Overview (Seer Interactive)
- Brands cited in AI Overviews also earn **91%** more paid clicks (Seer Interactive)
- Position 1 organic results lose the most traffic — an estimated **18–25%** click loss when an AI Overview appears above them (Advanced Web Ranking)

The data reveals a critical distinction: AI Overviews hurt sites that are not cited but significantly benefit sites that are. Being referenced inside the AI Overview is now arguably more valuable than ranking in position 1 below it.

### AI Overview Source Patterns

- **85%** of URLs cited in AI Overviews were published within the last **2 years** (Authoritas)
- AI Overviews tend to cite **3–5 sources** per response on average
- Pages with structured data markup are cited more frequently than pages without
- Long-form content (**2,000+ words**) appears in AI Overview citations more often than short-form content
- Content with specific data points and statistics earns citations at a higher rate than opinion-based content

## Zero-Click Search Statistics

Zero-click searches — queries where the user gets their answer directly on the search results page without clicking through to any website — have been rising for years. AI Overviews accelerate this trend.

### Current Zero-Click Rates

- **58.5%** of US Google searches end with zero clicks (SparkToro/Datos, 2024 study)
- Mobile zero-click rate: **77.2%** — more than 3 out of 4 mobile searches produce no click (SparkToro/Datos)
- Desktop zero-click rate: **46.5%** (SparkToro/Datos)
- In the EU, zero-click rates are slightly lower at **49.2%** due to regulatory requirements for Google to display more competitor links (SparkToro/Datos)
- Google clicks to the "open web" (non-Google properties) account for only **36.7%** of all US searches (SparkToro/Datos)

### What Zero-Click Means for SEO

The **58.5%** zero-click figure is frequently cited out of context. Important nuances:

- Many zero-click searches are navigational (users searching "Facebook login" or "BBC weather") — these were never going to produce exploratory clicks
- Informational zero-click searches include users getting answers from featured snippets, Knowledge Panels, and now AI Overviews
- Commercial and transactional queries still produce high click-through rates — users researching purchases still click through to product pages and reviews
- The **36.7%** "open web" click figure includes all industries. For B2B, e-commerce, and professional services, organic click rates remain substantially higher

Zero-click search reinforces the importance of being the cited source. If a user's query is answered on the search results page, the brand cited in that answer receives the visibility — even without the click. This directly parallels how [entity SEO](/blog/what-is-entity-seo/) builds brand recognition through search presence rather than clicks alone.

## AI Citation Patterns

Understanding which content AI platforms cite — and which they ignore — is essential for any [AI search optimisation](/services/ai-search-optimisation/) strategy. The data reveals surprising patterns.

### AI Citations vs Google Rankings

- Only **12%** of URLs cited by ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Copilot rank in Google's top 10 (The Digital Bloom)
- **80%** of AI-cited URLs do not rank in Google's top 100 at all (The Digital Bloom)
- This means traditional Google rankings are a poor predictor of AI citation probability
- Sites with low Google visibility can still earn substantial AI referral traffic through citation optimisation

This is the most consequential finding for SEO practitioners. The overlap between Google rankings and AI citations is remarkably small. A page buried on page 5 of Google can be the primary source cited by ChatGPT for a given query. AI platforms evaluate content quality, directness, and factual precision — not PageRank signals.

### Content Freshness Bias

- **50%** of Perplexity citations are content published in 2025 — a strong recency bias (Authoritas)
- **85%** of AI Overview citations were published within the last **2 years** (Authoritas)
- Older evergreen content that has not been updated is systematically overlooked by AI retrieval systems
- Content updated within the last **6 months** receives citation preference over identical content last updated 2+ years ago

Freshness matters more for AI citations than it does for traditional Google rankings. Google's index rewards established authority and backlink profiles. AI retrieval systems weight recency heavily because they prioritise current, accurate information. This means regular content updates are not just good practice — they are a prerequisite for AI visibility.

### What Content Gets Cited

Analysis across multiple studies and my own 44-site portfolio data reveals consistent patterns in AI-cited content:

- **Technical how-to content** — step-by-step guides with specific instructions earn the highest citation rates. In my portfolio, a technical troubleshooting guide earned **31,000+** Bing Copilot citations alone.
- **Research-backed content** — pages citing studies, data, and named sources receive citation preference over opinion pieces
- **Comprehensive single-page coverage** — content covering a topic thoroughly on one page outperforms content spread across multiple thin pages. This aligns directly with [topical authority](/services/topical-authority/) principles.
- **Direct answer formatting** — content structured with clear question headings and immediate answers in the first sentence of each section
- **Specific data points** — pages with named statistics, percentages, and figures are cited more frequently than pages with vague claims

Content that performs well for AI citations shares a common thread: it is the most useful, most specific, most directly answerable source available. [Optimising content for AI search](/blog/optimise-content-for-ai-search/) requires restructuring existing content around these patterns.

